data.content:
Here are the better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);  // if applicable
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));   // no built-in predicate assert; this is acceptable

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x == y)` | `Assert.AreEqual(x, y)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, list.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same elements, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The benefit: when tests fail, these give descriptive messages (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 2") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
